<div id="review_3886967449" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3886967449" />
    <a title="Jim Fonseca" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6743601-jim-fonseca"><img alt="Jim Fonseca" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1397669173p2/6743601.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3886967449?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim Fonseca" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim Fonseca" href="/user/show/6743601-jim-fonseca">Jim Fonseca</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679722342" href="/book/show/84743.Confessions_of_Zeno">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6743601-jim-fonseca?shelf=psychological-novel">psychological-novel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6743601-jim-fonseca?shelf=comic">comic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6743601-jim-fonseca?shelf=italian-authors">italian-authors</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3886967449" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15659587122362423830">Confessions of Zeno by Italo Svevo<br/><br/>Zeno is a good-hearted comic anti-hero. Everything works against him and just about everything he does to improve himself makes things worse. “I have, and have always had, a strong impulse to become better; this is perhaps my greatest misfortune.” <br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615605013i/31003950._SX540_.jpg' width='400' height='300' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>We start off with a full chapter about him trying to quit smoking cigarettes. He keeps track of his “last cigarette” which must now number in the hundreds. “I explained to him [his doctor] that giving up three meals a </span>
  <span id="freeText15659587122362423830" style="display:none">Confessions of Zeno by Italo Svevo<br><br>Zeno is a good-hearted comic anti-hero. Everything works against him and just about everything he does to improve himself makes things worse. “I have, and have always had, a strong impulse to become better; this is perhaps my greatest misfortune.” <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615605013i/31003950._SX540_.jpg" width="400" height="300" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>We start off with a full chapter about him trying to quit smoking cigarettes. He keeps track of his “last cigarette” which must now number in the hundreds. “I explained to him [his doctor] that giving up three meals a day seemed to me nothing compared with the task of making a fresh resolution every moment not to smoke another cigarette…I was really suffering from my resolutions much more than from the cigarettes.” <br><br>The novel is structured as a diary published by his doctor who was psychoanalyzing him. Zeno kept the account as part of his therapy. Much of the novel takes place in Trieste in northern Italy around the time of WW I. <br><br>Now take his marriage. Zeno has an older friend, a businessman who takes him under his wing. The older man has three daughters of marriageable age. Zeno courts the two good-looking daughters and ignores the third one whom he considers ugly. Guess which daughter he marries? That’s how Zeno’s life goes. <br><br>Zeno goes into business with his brother-in-law, the man who married Zeno’s wife’s beautiful sister. Their business is wholesaling goods. Neither man has any aptitude for business and they mainly chase the secretary around. Luckily Zeno has a stream of inherited wealth coming in.<br><br>Zeno has an affair and he manages to develop a relationship where when he is with his wife, he wishes he were with his mistress, and vice-versa. <br><br>I’m sure his shrink considered him a challenging case. LOL<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615605014i/31003951._SX540_.jpg" width="400" height="300" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Now this is fascinating. The book was set about the time of WWI and it was published in Italy in 1923. Here’s a prescient passage from the very last paragraph in the book: “When all the poison gases are exhausted, a man, made like all other men of flesh and blood, will in the quiet of his room invent an explosive of such potency that all the explosives in existence will seem like harmless toys beside it.” Wow. <br><br>I thought it was a good read and I enjoyed it, as I did another one of the author’s novels, Emilio’s Carnival. My rating of 4 is a 4.5 for quality writing rounded down for being a bit overly lengthy and dragged out a bit in places. This book, Confessions of Zeno, is also translated into English as Zeno’s Conscience. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615605117i/31003957.jpg" width="300" height="400" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The author (1861-1928) was a relatively unknown writer even in Italy until James Joyce, who lived in Trieste for more than ten years, spoke highly of his work. [And, according to my GR friend Nick Grammos, Svevo helped out Joyce financially.] In fact, as we are told in the introduction to Emilio’s Carnival, Svevo himself was an important model for Leopold Bloom in Ulysses and Svevo’s red-blonde-haired wife inspired the character Anna Livia Plurabelle in Joyce’s novel Finnegans Wake. After praise from Joyce, Svevo, who had given up writing, went on to write what some consider his masterpiece, Confessions of Zeno. (Others think Emilio’s Carnival is his best work.) Svevo was a pioneer of the psychological novel in Italy. <br><br>Photos of Trieste in the early 1900’s; top from gettyimages.com; second from alamy.com<br>The author on an Italian stamp from findyourstampsvalue.com</span>
  <a data-text-id="15659587122362423830" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


